rpna 1349","1270–1315":"1270–1315","1310–1367":"1310–1367","–1349":"–1349","1270":"1270","22 August 1349":"22. srpna 1349","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1367":"1367","1310":"1310","1453":"1453","Aft 8 October 1315":"po 8. října 1315","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Chipping Sodbury, Gloucestershire, England":"Chipping Sodbury, Gloucestershire, Anglie","Croston, Lancashire, England":"Croston, Lancashire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Greyfriars Church, Reading, Berkshire, England":"Greyfriars Church, Reading, Berkshire, Anglie","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"–22 August 1349":"–22. august 1349","1270–1315":"1270–1315","1310–1367":"1310–1367","–1349":"–1349","1270":"1270","22 August 1349":"22. august 1349","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1367":"1367","1310":"1310","1453":"1453","Aft 8 October 1315":"efter 8. oktober 1315","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Chipping Sodbury, Gloucestershire, England":"Chipping Sodbury, Gloucestershire, England","Croston, Lancashire, England":"Croston, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Greyfriars Church, Reading, Berkshire, England":"Greyfriars Church, Reading, Berkshire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"–22 August 1349":"–22 augustus 1349","1270–1315":"1270–1315","1310–1367":"1310–1367","–1349":"–1349","1270":"1270","22 August 1349":"22 augustus 1349","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1367":"1367","1310":"1310","1453":"1453","Aft 8 October 1315":"na 8 oktober 1315","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Chipping Sodbury, Gloucestershire, England":"Chipping Sodbury, Gloucestershire, England","Croston, Lancashire, England":"Croston, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Greyfriars Church, Reading, Berkshire, England":"Greyfriars Church, Reading, Berkshire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"–22 August 1349":"–22 August 1349","1270–1315":"1270–1315","1310–1367":"1310–1367","–1349":"–1349","1270":"1270","22 August 1349":"22 August 1349","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1367":"1367","1310":"1310","1453":"1453","Aft 8 October 1315":"after 8 October 1315","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Chipping Sodbury, Gloucestershire, England":"Chipping Sodbury, Gloucestershire, England","Croston, Lancashire, England":"Croston, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Greyfriars Church, Reading, Berkshire, England":"Greyfriars Church, Reading, Berkshire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Holland","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, German, Dutch, Danish, Norwegian, Swedish, French, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from <i>Holland</i>, a province of the Netherlands.","English: habitational name from Downholland or Upholland (Lancashire), Hulland (Derbyshire), the Parts of Holland, one of the three administrative subdivisions of Lincolnshire, any of the four places called Hoyland (southern Yorkshire), and possibly Great and Little Holland (Essex). The placenames all derive from Old English <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’.","English: habitational name either from Hoeland (Farm) in Bury (Sussex), or from Holland's Barn in Albourne (Sussex). The placename in Bury has the same etymology as in 1 above, while the placename in Albourne may derive from Old English <i>hol</i> ‘hole, hollow’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’."],"variants":[{"name":"Hollands","meanings":["English: variant of   Holland  , especially 3, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Dutch: genitivized form of   Holland  ."]},{"name":"Howland","meanings":["English: variant of   Holland  .","Americanized form of Norwegian   Hovland  .","History: Howland was the name of three Quaker brothers, original settlers in Marshfield, MA. They were from Huntingdonshire, England. The eldest, John Howland (<i>c.</i> 1593–1672) was a passenger on the <i>Mayflower</i>, servant to Gov. John Carver, who died in the first winter at Plymouth Colony."]},{"name":"Hollander","meanings":["Dutch (also <b>Den Hollander</b>), German (also <b>Holländer</b>), English, Swedish, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Holland (see   Holland   1)."]},{"name":"Holand","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Holland  .","Norwegian: habitational name from about twenty farmsteads so named, composed of Old Norse <i>hár</i> ‘high’ + <i>land</i> ‘land, field’, denoting a high-lying farm."]},{"name":"Aland","meanings":["Scandinavian (<b>Åland</b>): topographic name from the Åland Islands in the Gulf of Bothnia.","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>atte lande</i> (Old French <i>laund</i>) ‘dweller at the glade or pasture’, or sometimes perhaps, ‘dweller at the old cultivated land(s)’ from Old English <i>eald</i>, <i>ald</i> ‘old’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’."]},{"name":"Hollon","meanings":["English: altered form of   Holland  ."]}]},{"name":"Jane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":29,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":60,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":85,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":98,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":107,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Jane Holland was born in Lancashire, England, United Kin